{"id":"Q133259","names":{"en":"Almohad Caliphate","tr":"Muvahhidler","ar":"al-Muwahhidūn"},"country":["DZ","ES","LY","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1130,"extinct":1269},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"15","atlas_name_en_original":"The Almohads or al-Muwahhidūn","parent_tribe":"Masmūda Berberleri","ethnic_origin":"Berber (Masmūda)","capital":"Merakeş (Marrākush); İşbiliye (Seville - İspanya'da)","region_primary":"Kuzey Afrika ve İspanya","regions_all":"Fas; Cezayir; Tunus; Trablusgarb; Endülüs","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Murâbıtlar","successor":"Hafsîler (İfrîkıye); Abdülvâdîler (Tilimsân); Merînîler (Fas); Nasrîler (Gırnata)","government_type":"Hilafet","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Almohads rose through a radical religious reform movement based on Ibn Tumart's doctrine of divine unity, building the largest empire of the Islamic West from the Maghreb to the Iberian Peninsula. While patronizing philosophers like Ibn Rushd and Ibn Tufayl, their defeat at Las Navas de Tolosa (1212) initiated the empire's dissolution.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"31.63","capital_lon":"-8.01","century_start":12,"century_end":13}}
{"id":"Q132922","names":{"en":"Almoravid dynasty","tr":"Murâbıtlar","ar":"al-Murābitūn"},"country":["DZ","ES","MA"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1062,"extinct":1147},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"14","atlas_name_en_original":"The Almoravids or al-Murābitūn","parent_tribe":"Sanhāja Berberleri (Lamtūna, Gudāla)","ethnic_origin":"Berber (Sanhāja - Sahra)","capital":"Merakeş (Marrākush, 454/1062'de kuruldu)","region_primary":"Kuzeybatı Afrika ve İspanya","regions_all":"Fas; Batı/Orta Cezayir; Endülüs; Sahra; Moritanya","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Yerel Berber hanedanlar","successor":"Muvahhidler (Almohads)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Almoravids emerged from the veiled Sanhaja warriors of the Sahara, shaped by ribat discipline and spreading Maliki orthodoxy by the sword. Their victory at Zallaqa rescued al-Andalus from Christian advance while building a vast empire spanning the Maghreb to the Iberian Peninsula.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"31.63","capital_lon":"-8.01","century_start":11,"century_end":12}}
{"id":"royals:islamic-atlas:13","names":{"en":"Zīrids and Hammādid","tr":"Zîrîler ve Hammâdîler","ar":"al-Zīriyyūn wa al-Hammādiyyūn"},"country":["DZ","ES","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":972,"extinct":1152},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"13","atlas_name_en_original":"The Zīrids and Hammādids","parent_tribe":"Sanhāja Berberleri","ethnic_origin":"Berber (Sanhāja)","capital":"Kayrevân; al-Mahdiyye (Zîrîler); Qal'at Banī Hammād; Bicâye/Bougie (Hammâdîler)","region_primary":"Tunus ve Doğu Cezayir","regions_all":"İfrîkıye (Tunus); Doğu/Orta Cezayir; (Gırnata - İspanya kolu)","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Fâtımî valileri","successor":"Muvahhid fethi (547/1152); Norman işgali (Tunus kıyıları)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Zirids and Hammadids were Sanhaja Berber dynasties that transitioned from Fatimid service to independence. Zirid emir al-Mu'izz's declaration of Abbasid allegiance provoked the Fatimids to redirect the Hilalian and Sulaym Bedouin tribes toward the Maghreb, a migration wave that permanently altered North Africa's demographic structure.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"35.68","capital_lon":"10.10","century_start":10,"century_end":12}}
