{"id":"Q623573","names":{"en":"Aghlabid dynasty","tr":"Ağlebîler","ar":"al-Aghāliba"},"country":["DZ","IT","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":800,"extinct":909},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"11","atlas_name_en_original":"The Aghlabids","parent_tribe":"Horasanlı Arap komutan ailesi","ethnic_origin":"Arap","capital":"Kayrevân (al-Qayrawan); al-Raqqāda (geç dönem)","region_primary":"İfrîkıye (Tunus)","regions_all":"İfrîkıye; Cezayir; Sicilya; Malta; Güney İtalya kıyıları","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Abbâsî valileri","successor":"Fâtımîler","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Aghlabids transformed their Ifriqiyan governorship from the Abbasid caliph into de facto independence, conquering Sicily and carrying Islamic culture into Europe. They developed Kairouan as a center of learning and commerce while projecting naval power across the Mediterranean with raids on Italian coasts.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"35.68","capital_lon":"10.10","century_start":8,"century_end":10}}
