{"id":"Q1226593","names":{"en":"Zayyanid dynasty","tr":"Abdülvâdîler (Zeyyânîler)","ar":"Banū 'Abd al-Wād / al-Zayyāniyyūn"},"country":["DZ","MA"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1236,"extinct":1555},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"17","atlas_name_en_original":"The 'Abd al-Wādids or Zayyānids or Ziyānids","parent_tribe":"Zanāta Berberleri (Wāsīn)","ethnic_origin":"Berber (Zanāta)","capital":"Tilimsân (Tlemcen)","region_primary":"Batı Cezayir","regions_all":"Batı Cezayir; Tilimsân bölgesi","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Muvahhidler (vali olarak)","successor":"Osmanlı fethi (Cezayir Paşası Salāh Re'īs)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Abd al-Wadids were a Zanata Berber dynasty that established an independent principality centered on Tlemcen after the Almohad collapse. They prospered through Tlemcen's strategic position on east-west trade routes but remained perpetually squeezed between Marinid and Hafsid pressures, never achieving great imperial stature.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"34.88","capital_lon":"-1.31","century_start":13,"century_end":16}}
{"id":"Q620881","names":{"en":"Hafsid dynasty","tr":"Hafsîler","ar":"al-Hafsiyyūn"},"country":["DZ","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":1229,"extinct":1574},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"18","atlas_name_en_original":"The Hafsids","parent_tribe":"Hintātī Berberleri (Muvahhid geleneği)","ethnic_origin":"Berber","capital":"Tunus","region_primary":"Tunus ve Doğu Cezayir (İfrîkıye)","regions_all":"Tunus; Doğu Cezayir; Kostantîne; Bicâye","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":"Muvahhidler (vali olarak)","successor":"Osmanlı fethi (Sinān Paşa, 982/1574)","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":null,"narrative_en":"The Hafsids began as Almohad governors before gaining independence, becoming the most important dynasty of medieval Ifriqiya. They gained legitimacy through caliphal claims while revitalizing the region's intellectual tradition by introducing the madrasa system to Ifriqiya.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"36.81","capital_lon":"10.17","century_start":13,"century_end":16}}
{"id":"Q957197","names":{"en":"Rustamid dynasty","tr":"Rüstemîler","ar":"al-Rustamiyyūn"},"country":["DZ","MA","TN"],"category":"royal","period":{"founded":778,"extinct":909},"status":"extinct","head_current":null,"sources":["github:alicetinkaya76/islamic-civilization-atlas:all_dynasties_enriched.csv"],"raw":{"atlas_dynasty_id":"9","atlas_name_en_original":"The Rustamids","parent_tribe":"Fars kökenli (uydurma Sâsânî soyu)","ethnic_origin":"Fars","capital":"Tahert (Tāhart, bugünkü Tiaret yakını)","region_primary":"Tahert (Tāhart) - Batı Cezayir","regions_all":"Batı Cezayir; Aurés; Güney Tunus; Cebelinefûsa bağlantıları","geographic_zone":"Kuzey Afrika","predecessor":null,"successor":"Fâtımî fethi","government_type":"Hanedan/Beylik","religious_orientation":"Hâricî","narrative_en":"The Rustamids were an Iranian-origin dynasty established as the political center of the Kharijite Ibadi school, building the cosmopolitan city of Tahert, nicknamed the 'Iraq of the Maghreb.' They prospered through their connection to trans-Saharan trade networks while maintaining sectarian tolerance that sustained diverse communities.","importance_level":"Normal","capital_lat":"35.38","capital_lon":"1.32","century_start":8,"century_end":10}}
